      "(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0)` because the sum is positive.\n- And `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹ = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0)` because `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0) ≠ 0`.\n\nThus, `hpq` becomes `(↑(p i))⁻¹ + (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0) = (↑q)⁻¹`, and the goal is the same. \n\nBut in Lean, the expression `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹` is actually `(1 / (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0))⁻¹ = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0)`. \n\nHowever, Lean uses the coercion to `ℝ≥0∞` in `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹`, but in reality, `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹` is equal to `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` because `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)` is positive, so its inverse's inverse is itself. Similarly, `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹` is `(1 / (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0))⁻¹ = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0)` (as `NNReal`).\n\nBut `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)` is the same as `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0)` when coerced to `ℝ≥0∞`, because the coercion commutes with sums.\n\nTherefore:\n`(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞ = (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)` and `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0 = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0)`, and these two are equal when coerced to `ℝ≥0∞`.\n\nTherefore, the assumption is `(↑(p i))⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹) = (↑q)⁻¹`, and the goal is `(↑(p i))⁻¹ + (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0) = (↑q)⁻¹`, which are the same because `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞) = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0)` (as the coercion from `NNReal` to `ℝ≥0∞` commutes with sums).\n\nBut in Lean, `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0)` is a `NNReal`, and its coercion to `ℝ≥0∞` is `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)` because `(p i)⁻¹ : NNReal`, and coercion commutes with sums. \n\nThus, `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0` is `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0)` (since `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0) > 0` because `s.Nonempty`), and its coercion to `ℝ≥0∞` is `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)`.\n\nTherefore, in Lean's `hpq`, `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞ = (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)`, and `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞ = (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)`, because both are equal to the sum.\n\nBut Lean needs to realize that these are the same. \n\n**Realization of the Problem:**\nThe problem is that Lean's `hpq` is using `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹`, while the goal uses `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹`, and we need to show they are equal when coerced.\n\nHowever, note that:\n1. For any `a : NNReal`, `(a : ℝ≥0∞) = (a : ℝ≥0∞)`.\n2. `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞) = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : NNReal : ℝ≥0∞)`, because the coercion commutes with sums.\n3. For `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))",
      "(q)⁻¹` (in `ℝ≥0∞`) implies `(p i)⁻¹ + (↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹ = (q)⁻¹`, because both terms are the same when coercing to `ℝ≥0∞`.\n\nBut we need to be careful with coercions: in Lean, `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ : NNReal`, while `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞`. However, their coercion to `ℝ≥0∞` is the same.\n\nBut perhaps in `hpq`, the hypothesis is not quite the same. Looking back, in Lean the hypothesis is `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (q)⁻¹`, where `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ : NNReal` is coerced to `ℝ≥0∞`. \n\nBut the goal is to prove `(p",
