      "(↑q)⁻¹`.\n\nBut this is impossible because the problem is imposing conflicting definitions. Let's unpack the confusion:\n\n- `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹` in Lean (with real or extended-real coercions) is not the same as `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹`, because `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` coerces `p x` to `ℝ≥0` (or `ENNReal`) first, then takes the inverse as a real number, sums, and then takes inverses. On the other hand, `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)` first takes the inverse in `NNReal`, sums, then coerces to `ℝ≥0`.\n\nHowever, looking into Lean's coercions, `p : ι → NNReal`, so `(p i) : NNReal`, but `(↑(p i)) : ℝ≥0`, etc.\n\nBut `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : NNReal)` is the sum in `NNReal`, and `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹) : ℝ≥0` is the sum in `ℝ≥0`, and these are not the same when coerced back.\n\nBut Lean is not precise here because of coercions:\n`(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` is a sum in `ℝ≥0`, but `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)` is in `NNReal`, and `((∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : NNReal) : ℝ≥0)` is the coercion of the sum to `ℝ≥0`.\n\nBut there is no way that `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹` in general because `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` is `(↑∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)` (because coercion commutes with summation) but `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)` is different than `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x))⁻¹`.\n\n#### Calculating an Example\n\nLet `s = {1}` (as `Finset ι`), `p 1 = 2`, so `(↑(p 1))⁻¹ = 1/2` in `ℝ≥0`, and `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (1/2)⁻¹⁻¹ = 2⁻¹ = 1/2`.\n\nBut `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹) = (2⁻¹) = 1/2` in `NNReal`, then `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : NNReal)⁻¹ = 2`, and `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : NNReal)⁻¹)⁻¹ = (2 : ℝ≥0)⁻¹ = 1/2`.\n\nHuh, it actually works out?\n\nLet’s try another one: `s = {1, 2}`, `p 1 = p 2 = 2`.\n\nThen `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹) = 1/2 + 1/2 = 1`, then `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = 1⁻¹⁻¹ = 1⁻¹ = 1`.\n\n`(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹) = 1/2 + 1/2 = 1` in `NNReal`, `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹ = 1⁻¹ = 1`, `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹ = (1 : ℝ≥0)⁻¹ = 1`.\n\nStill works!\n\nAnother: `s = {1}`, `p 1 = 1`.\n\n`(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹) = 1⁻¹ = 1`, `(∑ x 